Ingredients
• 150 g fresh or frozen blueberries (about 1 cup)
• 2 tbsp sugar (preferably caster or fine granulated)
• 1½ tsp lemon juice
• 1 tsp honey (optional, for roundness)
• Pinch of salt
• 1–2 tbsp water, only if needed

Method
	1.	Combine blueberries, sugar, lemon juice, salt, and water in a small saucepan.
	2.	Cook over medium-low heat 6–8 minutes, stirring gently, until berries burst and release juice.
	3.	Simmer until lightly syrupy; do not over-reduce. The sauce should coat a spoon but remain fluid.
	4.	Optional refinement: strain half the sauce and recombine for a smoother, restaurant-style texture.
	5.	Cool slightly. Serve warm or room temperature.

How to Use with Honey Butter Toast
• Do not pour over the toast. Spoon around or beside the toast to preserve crispness.
• Use 1–2 tablespoons maximum per serving.
• Add ice cream or whipped cream only after the sauce is placed.

Chef Notes
• Lemon is essential; without acidity the sauce tastes jammy and heavy.
• Avoid cornstarch. Reduction alone gives cleaner flavor and mouthfeel.
• If serving in a high-end presentation, finish with 2–3 whole blueberries glazed in sauce rather than flooding the plate.

Custard Sauce (Crème Anglaise)

Ingredients
• 240 ml whole milk (1 cup)
• 2 large egg yolks
• 40 g sugar (3 tbsp)
• ½ tsp pure vanilla extract or vanilla bean paste
• Pinch of salt

Method
	1.	Heat milk with vanilla and salt just to steaming; do not boil.
	2.	Whisk yolks and sugar until pale and smooth.
	3.	Slowly temper the hot milk into the yolks while whisking.
	4.	Return to low heat and cook gently, stirring constantly, until the sauce thickens slightly and coats the back of a spoon (82–84°C / 180–183°F).
	5.	Immediately strain into a clean bowl to stop cooking. Cool slightly.

Proper Texture
The sauce should be pourable, not thick. If it resembles pudding, it is overcooked for this application.

How to Serve with Honey Butter Toast
• Spoon or pour around the toast, not directly on top.
• Use 2–3 tablespoons per plate.
• Best served warm or room temperature, never cold.

Chef Notes
• Avoid cornstarch. Egg-only custard delivers cleaner flavor and silkier mouthfeel.
• Salt is essential to prevent the sauce from tasting flat.
• For a Japanese café profile, reduce sugar slightly and rely on vanilla aroma for perceived sweetness.

